commentBody:
@Steve L 

You and I had much the same experience. 

Maybe my start at solving this was slow because I was sleepy, but my time was 25% higher than my all-time Friday average, and probably twice as long as Fridays usually take me now.

@Nick Roumel 

No 30 across — only down.



👁️👁️  👁️👁️  👁️👁️  Lookin' at you, Emu.

@michalightning 

We're always glad to have new commenters here.  

Welcome!

@sotto voce @Warren

Google "diet coke health effects" . . .

Coke or Pepsi, if you're drinking the diet version, it isn't healthy.  The tastiest Cokes are from Mexico, where they use sugar to sweeten them.

@TMD

The thing with the harder puzzles is that if you don't operate on the same wavelength as the constructor, you will struggle, and not in an enjoyable way. I also did not enjoy today's puzzle very much, but at the same time I can see how many people did - for me and you things did not click into place, for others they did.

A few months ago I did a Saturday puzzle in record time, only to later learn from the comments that a surprisingly huge part of the community found it hard and nasty.

@Pseudointellecual 
I appreciated Deb's column today, as well.  Her 'gimmes' are the same as mine.  I found I needed twenty cheats, as I really didn't want to struggle that much.  Maybe some other day, but not today....

I usually just go for 'fizzy water', aka Perrier water, or the Italian brand, because I can no longer do black tea (iced tea having been my old standby).  For me the question is "Is club soda okay" (the artificially bubbly one).

@Doggydoc 

I didn't get it.  THAT was MY problem with it.

PEPSI?  In the Land of CocaCola?  Fie!

@Eric Hougland I, too, am a member of the UPS/POTHERE club.

It’s interesting how well that misdirection worked, considering that POTHERE was never going to look right to anyone…and yet, I still filled in the puzzle with that “P” in place, and somehow even felt there was a non-minuscule chance I’d get the jingle.

Well played, Kate!

@Andrea Carla Michaels 
Don't you mean "a-peel to a Pepsi generation?"

Also, congrats again on receiving the Merl Reagle MEmoRiaL Award at this year's ACPT!

@Andrea Carla Michaels --"Except for my landlord situation" -- Hah!

Glad to see you here!






Et tu, emu.

@Janine 

Oh it's real.  The reason they mounted a long and exhausting series of "Pepsi Challenge" commercials was based on the fact that Pepsi just tastes better as shown in those earlier blind tests.  Or at least sweeter enough that it always wins a blind tasting.

I far, far prefer it to Coke, which always tastes like an acidic mess.  But in practice I drink neither.  Sodas are a fine food (really) but not my thing overall.

@Francis 

Nine for SSN, as I’m sure you know. 

I think I needed two out of three letters to come up with TEL. It’s only been a few years since Austin got a second “area code” and you had to dial 10 digits for local calls.

@Richard Eyster 

Of course you speak only for yourself and I speak only for myself but I have had many flight attendants and servers and bartenders ask if Pepsi was okay. 

I thought this puzzle was a delight and though it's totally fine that you didn't, to immediately be like oh this was self congratulatory and whatever, is a bit silly.

@Dan 

Thank you 🙂

The American sports clues are some of the hardest ones in NYT puzzles for me, and when they are about abbreviations on top of that, I am hopelessly in the dark, without any hope of finding a solution.

@ktel 

Up where the Settings icon is, there’s one that’s supposed to represent a ring-shaped life preserver. Autocheck and similar “hints” are there. 

Please wish your friend happy solving.
